{"/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_garnet_ver01/data/sn87065643/00383344475/1907121201/0018.xml":{"full_text":"Th\n\u25a0\u25a0\u2014\u00ab\u2014\u2014\u2014mmmmtim\nH. A. LEE, Editof \"Devoted to the Interest of th\nVOLUME, 14 WATER VALLEY, MISS., DECEMBER 12, 190? NU1\n*___._&_- 1 __\nOn the 25th instant\u2014which is\nright over yonder, and which is too\nnear to some of us Unprepared fel\nlows to bring a comfortable feeU\ning\u2014Santa Claus and the Financial\nPanic will shake hands over the\nbloody Chasm \u2014Santa with a smile\nand Old Panic with a frown. San\nta, we understand, got hold of\nenough script somewhere to pur\nchase Christmas things with which\nto supplement the stock that could\nnot be made at his Arctic Facto\nries, and he is coming loaded, not\nwithstanding the strengency. San\nta never gives strengency any con\nsideration. He is light hearted to\nbeat six bits, consequently he is\nwell preserved. He doesn\u2019t look\nany older now than he did a thou\nsand years ago. If you hear a\nnoise up the chimney just keep\nquiet and saw wood. It won\u2019t be\nMr. Hyde. The nearer you can\ncome being asleep the better, it\nmakes the surprise on the morning\nof the 25th more enrapturing. Be\ncertain and keep these suggestions\nin your head. Keep cool and you\nwill forget the panic for a season.\nMrs. Julia Morehead, of Mc\nComb, on her way to visit relatives\nand friends in Centralia, 111, stop\nped over and spent Saturday and\nSunday in our city the guest of\nMrs. J. H. Garland.\nMessrs. Harry Cullinane and\nFred Myers, two of the I C.\u2019s pop\nular firemau, were recently promo\nted to the responsible place of En\ngineers, and are now directing the\nenergies of the iron horse over the\nrails of the great I. C.\nMany a man neglects to get a\nmove on himself because he has a\nfool wife who thinks he is too\ngood-looking to work.\n\nMiss Lucile Reeves left last\nTuesday morning for an extended\nvisit to relatives in the Delta.\nThe Moving Picture Show at the\nW. O. Robinson old stand, is do*\ning a better business than ever be*\ntore. The hall is full ever night\nfor each show given to see the best\nMoving Pictures on the market.\nShow every half hour from 7 to 10\no\u2019clock, Prices 5 and 10 cents,\nMr. Glenn Connor, formerly of\nour city, holding while \u201ehere the\nresponsible position of Yard Mas\nter for the I. C. R. R., but now of\nChicago, having been promoted to\nthe position of Traveling Auditor,\nwas united in marriage Wednes\nday to Miss Leah Evans, of Car\nbondale, 111, He began railroad\ning in our city, and rapidly rose\nto his present position. He is\nmuch esteemed by our people, and\nis popular both socially and in a\nbusiness sense. The editor of The\nItemizer extends his hand and\nwishes him many years of happi\nness and contentment in this new\nrelation in life.\nMr, Will Dalton, who joined the\nNaval Service of Uncle Sam a few\nmonths since, returned home sev\neral days ago. Defective eyes un\nfitted him for the duties of his po\nsition and he received an honora\nble discharge.\nYes, we are feeling a good deal\nbetter, we thank you! Our back\nbone has been greatly strengthen\ned and our ribs fortified. Our res\nolution is returning. It would\nnever have been done but for the\nuses to which the anatomy of a\nhog can be put. Our good friend,\nMr, W. C. Southwick, who is a\nclose observer of conditions, noted\nour slab-sidedness, and immediate\nly came forward with a remedy in\nthe shape of a hog\u2019s spine and\nribs, and fitted us up for a prose\ncution of our duties, From the\nvery first application we felt re\nlieved, Our hat is off to him right\nnow.\nMrs. 8. Ei Cooper spe\ndays in Memphis last wet\nMr, C. E. Garland; of\n111., was a visitor to his old\nin our city last Week, the gue^\nhis brother, Mr, J. H. Garland^!\nMiss BellefBlack and little\nleft last week for a visit of eevera 4\nweeks to relatives and friends in\nAckerman.\n\nMr, and Mrs, Fred Pearson left\nlast. Saturday morning for a few\ndays\u2019 visit to friends in Canton,\nMr. W. J, King and daughter,\nMiss Ethel, left Saturday night for\na few days\u2019 visit to Jackson.\nMr, E W. Smith, of Owensboro,\nKy., spent last Thursday in our\ncity the guest of his mother, Mrs.\nS. E. Smith.\nMrs. W. T. Harrison, of Oxford,\nattended the marriage of Mr. Roy\nMyers and Miss Byrt Payne in our\ncity last Thursday.\n--wa>-\nMr. Bester Holcombe has ac\ncepted a position with A. B. Por\nter, and invites his friends to call\nand trade with him.\nMrs. Sam Stanford and children,\nof Carrollton, are in the city for\na two weeks\u2019 visit to Mrs, Will\nRobinson,\nMrs. W, J. Royul and little son,\nMaster Walter, jr., spent a day or\ntwo in Grenada last week.\nMrs. Walter Mills and children\nreturned last week from a several\ndays\u2019 visit to Oxford,\nJudge J. C, Wilson was down\nfrom .Memphis last week looking\nafter business before the Chancery\nCourt.\nDr, W. E. Jenkins, formerly a\nresident of our county, but now\nAssistant Physician of the Insane\nHospital in Jackson, was in the\ncity last Tuesday.","height":"13000","width":"9940"}}
